<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08178n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08178n">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08178n"> 178(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ollove (12 yrs) knew 250 romances</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Caesar tells us that the Gauls of history had trained reciters who could carry in their mind an incredible number of poems. When the institution was fully developed among the Irish an <i>ollave</i> or chief poet was bound to know by heart two hundred and fifty of the chief stories and one hundred of the secondary romances. For this perfection a training of twelve years was held necessary. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 10</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The ollamh was the highest dignitary amongst the bards, and it took him from nine to twelve years&apos; training to learn the two hundred and fifty prime stories and the one hundred secondary ones along with the other things which were required of him. </mm> </dd></dl>
